topic.title: Unauthorized files appearing in my IFS Cluster
topic.body:
So did the usual daily check of the proxy status and found some files in IFS Cluster 1 that I didn't seed nor authorize to host. I have my proxy UI restricted to my local IP and I don't have auto seeding enabled on the IFS cluster so I'm a bit clueless as to how the file appeared.

The file in question was `Michael_Caine_with_a_young_girl___Watch_online.mp4`
Which appeared on the proxy about two hours ago from writing this comment. Doing a search on IFS doesn't reveal the file so it must have been deleted or renamed.

I did some further digging and I'm adding the user to my local blacklist to prevent future incidences from that user as they also have rape material published, so I am only left to speculate the legality of the 'young girl' video as well.

1589915224_14ADWoY886HnM8jPeipXarxAfyQAN.body:
Maybe it is due to bad labeling?
The IFS Channel Music and Music Z has published "Two Steps From Hell" titles along with a collection of others that are visible to me.

Maybe check files?  Also Zeronet doesn't auto PIN small files such as mp3s. So the uploader will need to go 'PIN' all 200 mp3s to ensure the local client doesn't auto remove them over time.

Not pinning smaller files is a design in  Zeronet rather than IFS

I really think the problem might be local as I can see 210 Music files posted by Music Z, it this the same total that you see?

It is possible somehow the data or user json file for that account got corrupted and the listing appears partial on your end?

If you have a name of a file I can check to see if I can still see it on my end and even post a link directly to that mp3 to see if your able to redownload it, or if it loads but is just an invisible listing to you.

IFS's normalization of names is not perfect, I've posted file with special characters int hem that not only failed to seed, but I had to go and manually remove the entry by editing the json file manually.

When doing a search of "Two steps from hell" i see a total listing of 8 files, is this the same number that you have or should it have been more?

Also when a user does a bulk posting to IFS, the first item will be published immediately, but the user has to wait 20 seconds or so for a second update to be pushed through for the rest of the bulk items to get processed.

If the user closes their client before the second update from the bulk publish, only the first item will have been published and the rest of the bulk items would have fallen to pending.

I have a bunch of work out EDM music published & pined to ensure longevity, but I try to not bulk upload any more than 20 or so at a time just because the platform is still flakey. It is very possible for large bulk uploads to not be signed or failed to be signed.

But for a platform that is impervious to DMCA takedowns, I'll deal with it.

PS Edit: Also when I had a similar problem with IFS, I ended up  creating a new VPS with a fresh zeronet install, then I migrating that user ID to the new proxy, and once the ID was appearing as valid in ZeroiD, I loaded up IFS and all my previous files from that account was autod ownloaded to the new VPS, in which I then later deleted the old corrupted VPS.

But otherwise, the files posted from 8 hours ago are still visible and work for me:
[Revolt Production Music_Infinite By: Music-Z](/12MVkvYGcRW6u2NYbpfwVad1oQeyG4s9Er/index.html?view:item+id:15f1_14ADWoY886HnM8jPeipXarxAfyQANiMTQj_item_119+type:audio)

> [bitwolf](#comment_33_1Kq1ox6SsERUFsQjyGCLKf7EuHJuDs3wfu): and a total of 83 results when clicking on music-Z's name.

How strange... mine shows 210 when I click on his name...

> [tnytuqsgqnywmecj](#comment_20_19y1ZG2DVeRM65kYxKcLz7MLGTfTfoUWSm): People need to SEED your content..

People who upload and expect other zeronet users to seed their content for them are using the zeronet network incorrectly...

If your going to upload something, one should at least be polite enough to keep their uploads PINNED and well seeded. After all, if the uploader has not found it worthy to keep their own material seeded, then why would anyone else?

The ability for other people to seed material WITH you is the intent of the network in that your client is not the sole provider of the material and to carry the sole burden of distribution as seen with conventional file hosting providers.

Take the documentaries I share for example. Sure it is a strain on the proxy if it is the only one distributing that material, but when other people begin to view and deem the material is also worthy of their time, space, and bandwidth, does my own proxy begin to show a lightening of the load and the health and speed of the transmission of such material is dramatically increased. (Which is the true magic of zeronet)

> PLUS there needs to be enough people for your node / client to pick up other locations hosting your files.

His node should be the only node needed to locate his files considering he is the uploader...

> [tnytuqsgqnywmecj](#comment_21_19y1ZG2DVeRM65kYxKcLz7MLGTfTfoUWSm):  however the PINNED content is only for 24 hours and such is NOT permanent! .

You are incorrect, a file is pinned will last indefinitely... I have shared titles from over two years ago and their status is still pinned.

If there is a delay in uploads it is likely because that node that published it is behind Tor, has inconsistent availability, (like someone's home pc), or is having a problem announcing their connectivity to the trackers. (Syncronite helps with that)

> Surely the list was in my phone while this happened. Probably something different from a dead share happened, maybe a cluster corruption that spread between all nodes of the network? 

We early adopters have to remember that many of the sites we publish on were just working proofs of concepts. Many expected their site to be used as templates for others to improve upon. Not to adopt and use. But I also understand that we must make due with what we have.

After owning a zeronet proxy for over three years and seeding material from it. I would say I had my fair share of problems due to flakey bugs in the network. But my advice is to just be persistent. The clearnet was full of bugs and we as users had little problem adapting to those annoyances as well.

For example, when I publish material to IFS on my local client, I then go seed  it in my proxy so that I can then close my local client and keep my material seeded. Well, when uploading music to IFS, on the proxy I have to go to each file and play the mp3 and even advance the track position until the status bar shows 100% File Completed

Because every time I just click a mp3, or load a file and then browse away from the page, the mp3 will only load to %50 or so on the proxy (even though my local client is still running) which left unfixed will leave my proxy with an incomplete copy.

Once the file shows File Finished on the IFS status bar, I then go to those files and then PIN them on the proxy to ensure persistence. I've successfully used this method to keep music pinned in IFS for over a year without problem.

I PIN both the file as well as the .msgpack file to ensure persistence.
IFS is not IPFS, Pinning a file is based on your Zeronet client, not IPFS. My files have never unpinned themselves by themselves...

> [tnytuqsgqnywmecj](#comment_34_19y1ZG2DVeRM65kYxKcLz7MLGTfTfoUWSm): can post content via IFS and view such via IPFS.

Really? I have the [IPFS client](https://docs.ipfs.io/guides/guides/install/) installed, please elaborate as to how I can get it to interact with the IFS Zeronet site? Like what is the console command that I would use to retrieve such files from, let's say my proxy's IFS Cluster 1, and then locally host them in the IPFS file ledger?
